<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
    The <a href="/backlog/1656-conformance-lit-extension-funnel-mvp-chrome-devtools-panel-t/">conformance-lit
    funnel MVP (#1656)</a> is the first fundable dev-surface build per <a href="/backlog/1590-dev-surface-monetization-bet-extensions-as-funnel-vs-dev-bro/">#1590</a>:
    a Chrome / DevTools-panel extension whose tooling <strong>lights up only on a WE-conformant app</strong>.
    The buried fork at its heart (carved out as <a href="/backlog/1673-conformance-lit-mvp-how-does-the-extension-detect-we-conform/">#1673</a>):
    <strong>how does the extension decide a running page is WE-conformant?</strong> No live-page probe exists
    today. Three mutually-exclusive mechanisms are on the table:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>(a) DECLARED</strong> — the app ships a <code>CapabilityManifest</code> the extension reads
        (the <code>we:capability-manifest/</code> schema).</li>
    <li><strong>(b) PROBED</strong> — the extension inspects the live runtime for WE signals (the scoped
        custom-element registry, the webexpressions binding layer, context providers), needing no app
        cooperation.</li>
    <li><strong>(c) VERIFIED</strong> — run conformance vectors / the engine against the live page.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    This survey grounds the call in how <em>shipping</em> framework devtools detect their framework on a live
    page, the recurring trade space that pattern reveals, and the WE machinery already in the tree — so the
    rule reuses precedent vocabulary rather than coining its own.
</p>

<h2>How shipping framework devtools detect a live page</h2>
<p>
    Every widely-used framework devtool faces exactly this problem — "is my framework on this page, and how do
    I light up?" — and they have converged on a dominant answer: <strong>probe a runtime signal the framework
    leaves on the page</strong>, never gate on a manifest the app must opt into, never run a verification suite
    merely to decide whether to activate.
</p>

<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Tool / detector</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Signal it reads</th><th>Cooperation needed?</th><th>Failure mode</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td>React DevTools</td>
            <td>Probe — global hook + DOM-node tag</td>
            <td><code>window.__REACT_DEVTOOLS_GLOBAL_HOOK__</code> (React injects it at renderer init); DOM
                nodes carry <code>__reactFiber$…</code> (React 18+) / <code>__reactInternalInstance$…</code></td>
            <td>None — React registers the hook for the devtool to find</td>
            <td>Version drift across fiber-property names; minified internals</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Vue DevTools</td>
            <td>Probe — global + per-element app handle</td>
            <td><code>window.__VUE__</code> / <code>window.__VUE_DEVTOOLS_GLOBAL_HOOK__</code>;
                <code>el.__vue_app__</code> on mounted roots</td>
            <td>None</td>
            <td>Vue 2 vs 3 global shape divergence</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Angular devtools</td>
            <td>Probe — root attribute + global</td>
            <td><code>ng-version</code> attribute on the root element (rendered even under SSR — the most
                robust fingerprint); the <code>ng</code> global</td>
            <td>None — but the attribute is a declared-by-the-framework marker, the probe/declared hybrid</td>
            <td>Production builds can strip <code>ng</code>; the attribute survives</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Svelte devtools</td>
            <td>Probe — best-effort, weakest signal</td>
            <td>Svelte compiles to vanilla JS; <strong>no runtime global</strong> — only <code>svelte-</code>
                prefixed CSS classes hint at it</td>
            <td>None</td>
            <td><strong>Cautionary case:</strong> a compile-away framework leaves almost no probe surface — the
                hardest major framework to detect programmatically</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Wappalyzer / Lighthouse stack-packs / BuiltWith</td>
            <td>Probe — generalized signature matching</td>
            <td>In-page JS with full <code>window</code>+DOM access matching ~3000 signatures: globals
                (<code>window.__NUXT__</code>), DOM properties/attributes, CSS class patterns, headers, meta
                tags</td>
            <td>None (browser-execution mode)</td>
            <td>Documented as <strong>unreliable</strong>: false positives, version drift, minification</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>PWA web-app-manifest / security.txt / .well-known</td>
            <td><strong>Declared</strong> — opt-in self-description</td>
            <td>A static JSON/text artifact the app publishes (the DECLARED analog)</td>
            <td><strong>Required</strong> — the app must ship it</td>
            <td>Can lie / go stale; needs app cooperation; ~93% fetched over HTTP (tamperable)</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
