<h2>The recurring trade space</h2>
<p>
    Across both the framework-devtool precedent and the manifest family, three postures recur — and they are
    the same three branches #1673 names:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Declared-manifest (a)</strong> — opt-in, trustable, self-describing, version-stamped. But it
        needs app cooperation, <em>can lie</em>, and <em>goes stale</em> against the running code. No shipping
        framework devtool gates its first-impression on one.</li>
    <li><strong>Runtime-probe (b)</strong> — zero cooperation, widest reach, the de-facto standard for every
        framework devtool. But brittle to minification / version drift and prone to false positives (the
        Wappalyzer-unreliability and Svelte-invisibility lessons).</li>
    <li><strong>Verification (c)</strong> — authoritative (it actually exercises behaviour, not just presence).
        But expensive / slow, and — decisively for a passive light-up gate — it <em>mutates the live page</em>
        (renders elements, dispatches events). No devtool runs a test suite merely to decide whether to
        activate.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The WE machinery already in the tree</h2>
<p>
    Each branch maps onto concrete WE code, which fixes how much each costs and what each can actually read on
    a live page <em>today</em>:
</p>
