<p>
    A decisive in-tree fact: a DECLARED-only gate would today light up on <strong>zero</strong> pages, because
    no implementation ships a runtime manifest (<code>we:capability-manifest/check.ts:107</code>). And VERIFIED
    mutates the page, so it disqualifies itself as the always-on activation gate. That leaves PROBE as the only
    branch that can be the <em>default</em> first-impression mechanism for the MVP — exactly the conclusion the
    framework-devtool precedent reaches independently.
</p>

<h2>The three-branch mapping and recommendation</h2>
<p>
    The framework-devtool precedent, the trade space, and the in-tree facts all point the same way for a
    <strong>free funnel's widest-reach first impression</strong> (the #1590/#1656 frame): <strong>probe-first,
    tiered to a declared upgrade and a verify-on-demand action</strong>.
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Default — PROBE to light up.</strong> The extension reads the WE runtime signals that exist
        with no app cooperation (scoped-registry markers; injector-chain providers; webexpressions presence).
        Widest reach, the universal framework-devtool pattern, non-mutating, and the only branch that lights up
        on real pages today.</li>
    <li><strong>Upgrade — DECLARED as the authoritative opt-in.</strong> When an app <em>does</em> ship a
        runtime <code>CapabilityManifest</code>, the extension prefers it: it carries the precise
        <code>conformanceLevel</code> and feature set the probe can only infer, and it is the trustable
        self-description the rich-vision per-feature lighting (#141 Fork 1) already assumes. It is an
        <em>enhancement layer over</em> the probe, not a replacement gate.</li>
    <li><strong>On-demand — VERIFY as an inspector action, never the passive gate.</strong> Running the
        conformance engine against the live page is authoritative but mutating and slow; it belongs behind an
        explicit "run conformance" button in the panel, not on the always-on light-up path.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    This is the canonical <strong>tiered detection</strong> shape: probe is the floor (zero-cooperation
    reach), declared is the ceiling (trustable precision when offered), verify is the on-demand deep check.
    The sub-fork prep surfaces — "probe-to-light + verify-on-demand tiering" — is therefore not a rival to the
    main fork but the recommended <em>composition</em> of all three, with probe as the default activation gate.
</p>

